04244nam a22007215i 9781474468954DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222001stk    fo  d z      eng d  a97814744689547 a10.1515/97814744689542doi  a(DE-B1597)615545  a(OCoLC)1306540355  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  astkcGB-SCT 7aPOL0000002bisacsh04a330.1222211 aHarvey, David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSpaces of Capital :bTowards a Critical Geography /cDavid Harvey. 1aEdinburgh : bEdinburgh University Press, c[2022] 4c©2001  a1 online resource (432 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tSources -- tPROLOGUE -- tPart 1 GEOGRAPHICAL KNOWLEDGES/POLITICAL POWER -- tPart 2 THE CAPITALIST PRODUCTION OF SPACE -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDavid Harvey is unquestionably the most influential, as well as the most cited, geographer of his generation. His reputation extends well beyond geography to sociology, planning, architecture, anthropology, literary studies and political science. This book brings together for the first time seminal articles published over three decades on the tensions between geographical knowledges and political power and on the capitalist production of space. Classic essays reprinted here include 'On the history and present condition of geography', 'The geography of capitalist accumulation' and 'The spatial fix: Hegel, von Thünen, and Marx'. Two new chapters represent the author's most recent thinking on cartographic identities and social movements. David Harvey's persistent challenge to the claims of ethical neutrality on behalf of science and geography runs like a thread throughout the book. He seeks to explain the geopolitics of capitalism and to ground spatial theory in social justice. In the process he engages with overlooked or misrepresented figures in the history of geography, placing them in the context of intellectual history. The presence here of Kant, Von Thünen, Humboldt, Lattimore, Leopold alongside Marx, Hegel, Heidegger, Darwin, Malthus, Foucault and many others shows the deep roots and significance of geographical thought. At the same time David Harvey's telling observations of current social, environmental, and political trends show just how vital that thought is to the understanding of the world as it is and as it might be.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCapitalism. 0aCommunism and geography. 0aMarxian economics. 0aSpace in economics. 0aUrban economics. 0aUrban geography. 4aGeography. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000z97831107804680 cprintz978074861541440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978147446895440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781474468954423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781474468954/original  a978-3-11-078046-8  Edinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK